    title: 'Consciousness and Integrated Information Theory',
    text: "The hard problem of consciousness questions how subjective experience arises from physical processes. Integrated Information Theory proposes consciousness corresponds to a system's capacity for integrated information, quantified by phi. A system possesses consciousness to the extent it generates information exceeding the sum of its parts, through causal interactions within rather than between partitions. The theory identifies qualia with shapes in conceptual space and explains intentionality through relationships among informational states. Predictions include consciousness in systems with appropriate architecture regardless of substrate, potentially including artificial systems. Empirical tests involve perturbational complexity index measurements in brain networks. Criticisms address phi's computational intractability for large systems, counterintuitive implications regarding consciousness distribution, and relationship to neural correlates. Alternative frameworks include global workspace theory emphasizing information accessibility and higher-order theories requiring meta-representation. IIT represents a mathematically rigorous approach deriving consciousness from first principles rather than correlating it with neural activity. Its development exemplifies the interdisciplinary convergence of neuroscience, information theory, and philosophy addressing fundamental questions about subjective experience's place in the natural world.", audioUrl: 'https://storage.googleapis.com/pte_flow_audio/speaking/retell_lecture/130.mp3',
    image: null,
    modelAnswer: "The speaker examines consciousness through Integrated Information Theory, proposing consciousness corresponds to integrated information capacity (phi). Consciousness arises from causal interactions generating information exceeding partitioned sums. Theory identifies qualia with conceptual shapes and predicts substrate-independent consciousness. Empirical tests use complexity measurements; criticisms address computability and implications. Alternatives include global workspace and higher-order theories. IIT represents interdisciplinary convergence deriving consciousness from first principles, addressing subjective experience's place in nature."
