    id: '131',
    title: 'Derridas Deconstruction and Différance',
    text: "Jacques Derrida's deconstruction constitutes not a method but a reading strategy revealing how texts undermine their own philosophical assumptions through internal contradictions. Différance, a neologism combining differing and deferring, signifies how meaning arises from relationships within linguistic systems rather than reference to external reality. The logic of supplementarity shows how additions reveal original inadequacies. Binary oppositions privileging one term over another (speech/writing, nature/culture) become unstable through careful analysis showing each term depending on its supposed opposite. Metaphysics of presence, the Western philosophical tradition privileging immediate presence, becomes problematic given mediation through signs and temporal deferral. Deconstruction operates not by destroying structures but demonstrating their inherent instability and conditions of possibility. Applied beyond philosophy to legal, literary, and political texts, it reveals how excluded margins haunt and constitute centers. Criticisms include alleged nihilism, political quietism, and methodological obscurity. Responses emphasize deconstruction's ethical dimension attending to otherness and its utility for critical intervention in discourses of power. While peak influence has passed, deconstruction's legacy persists in heightened sensitivity to language, representation, and the politics of conceptual hierarchies across humanities disciplines.", audioUrl: 'https://storage.googleapis.com/pte_flow_audio/speaking/retell_lecture/131.mp3',
    image: null,
    modelAnswer: "The speaker discusses Derrida's deconstruction as a reading strategy revealing textual self-undermining through internal contradictions. Différance signifies meaning from linguistic relationships rather than external reference. Analysis destabilizes binary oppositions and critiques metaphysics of presence. Deconstruction demonstrates structural instability, applied across disciplines to reveal how margins constitute centers. Criticisms address nihilism and obscurity; responses highlight ethical dimensions and critical utility. Its legacy persists in sensitivity to language, representation, and conceptual hierarchy politics."
